          'Zipminator is structured as a seven-layer system with strict separation of concerns. Each layer communicates only with its immediate neighbors through well-defined interfaces. This layered architecture ensures that changes in the presentation layer (adding a new Flutter screen, for example) never touch the cryptographic core, and that improvements in the entropy layer propagate to all nine pillars without requiring per-pillar modifications. The architecture is not theoretical; it is the actual structure of the deployed codebase, verified by 1,616 tests across all layers.',
          'Layer 1, the Presentation Layer, consists of three client applications. The Flutter super-app (app/) targets macOS, iOS, Android, Windows, Linux, and Web from a single Dart codebase using Material 3 theming with the quantum design system (cyan, purple, green accent palette). The Next.js web dashboard (web/) at zipminator.zip serves the investor blueprint, waitlist, and public-facing landing pages with OAuth via GitHub, Google, LinkedIn, and Apple. The Python CLI (src/zipminator/cli/) provides command-line access to all SDK functions through Typer with Rich formatting. All three clients are stateless with respect to cryptographic operations; they delegate every security-sensitive computation to layers below.',
          'Layer 2, the Application Layer, handles routing, authentication, and session management. The FastAPI server (api/) exposes REST endpoints for encrypt, decrypt, anonymize, and key management operations. JWT authentication with SHA-256 API key hashing protects every endpoint. Redis-backed rate limiting prevents abuse. PostgreSQL stores operation audit logs, API key records, and user sessions. The Flutter super-app uses Riverpod 3 with seven Notifier providers (crypto, ratchet, pii, email, vpn, srtp, theme) managing all pillar state through immutable state objects. GoRouter with ShellRoute provides responsive navigation across all form factors.',
          'Layer 3, the Service Layer, implements the nine-pillar business logic. Each pillar (Vault, Messenger, VoIP, VPN, Anonymizer, Q-AI, Email, Browser, Q-Mesh) is a separate service module that consumes cryptographic primitives from Layer 4 but makes its own decisions about protocol sequencing, state machines, and user-facing behavior. The PQ Double Ratchet protocol in the Messenger pillar, for instance, decides when to perform ratchet steps, how to manage offline message queues, and how to handle group fanout, but it delegates every ML-KEM-768 operation to the crypto core. This separation means a new pillar can be added by implementing service logic alone, without modifying the cryptographic engine.',
          'Layer 4, the Crypto Core, is the security-critical center of the system. Written entirely in Rust for memory safety and constant-time guarantees, the zipminator-core crate implements CRYSTALS-Kyber-768 (NIST FIPS 203 ML-KEM) with Number Theoretic Transform (NTT) using in-place Cooley-Tukey butterfly operations, Montgomery reduction for modular multiplication, and the subtle crate for constant-time branching via ConstantTimeEq and ConditionallySelectable. Key sizes are: public key 1,184 bytes, secret key 2,400 bytes, ciphertext 1,088 bytes, shared secret 32 bytes. The core also implements the PQ Double Ratchet (HKDF-SHA-256 chain keys with ML-KEM-768 ratchet steps), PQ-SRTP (ML-KEM-768 master key derivation with AES-256-GCM frame encryption), PII scanning (18 regex pattern categories), and email crypto (ML-KEM-768 envelope with AES-256-GCM payload). All secret data is zeroized on drop.',
          'Layer 5, the Entropy Layer, provides cryptographic randomness to the core. The EntropyManager maintains a priority-ordered list of entropy sources. Priority 1 is real quantum entropy from IBM Quantum hardware (6.8 MB harvested from 35 jobs on ibm_kingston, 156 qubits, stored in pre-harvested pool files). Priority 2 is CSI-derived entropy from WiFi Channel State Information using the PUEK construction. Priority 3 is the OS kernel CSPRNG (/dev/urandom). The thread-safe EntropyPool buffers 4 KB to 64 KB of random data with a background refill worker that triggers when the buffer drops below 16 KB. Health monitoring checks each source every 60 seconds. The three entropy pools are provenance-separated (quantum, CSI, OS) with no cross-contamination. The CompositorProvider XOR-fuses pools for applications that require composed entropy, with Merkle provenance chains tracking the origin of every byte.',
          'Layer 6, the Storage Layer, handles persistent data. The Quantum Vault uses AES-256-GCM with ML-KEM-768-derived keys for file encryption, supporting CSV, JSON, Parquet, and Excel formats. The DoD 5220.22-M three-pass overwrite (zeros, ones, random bytes) implements self-destruct for the highest-security tier. The password vault in ZipBrowser uses Argon2 key derivation with ML-KEM-768 encrypted entries. All encrypted data includes Merkle-certified provenance linking each ciphertext to the entropy source, the key generation event, and the encryption timestamp. SQLite provides local structured storage for session state, message histories, and configuration, while PostgreSQL handles server-side persistence for the API layer.',
          'Layer 7, the Transport Layer, secures all data in motion. PQ-WireGuard (ML-KEM-768 handshake replacing Curve25519) provides device-wide VPN tunneling with a kill switch that drops all traffic if the tunnel fails. WebSocket signaling via wss://zipminator-signaling.fly.dev on Fly.io handles real-time communication for the Messenger and VoIP pillars. PQC TLS proxying in ZipBrowser intercepts HTTPS connections and performs ML-KEM-768 key exchange where supported. QUIC transport (TLS 1.3 AEAD) secures aggregator uplinks in the Q-Mesh pillar, while ESP32-S3 mesh nodes use HMAC-SHA256 beacon authentication and SipHash-2-4 frame integrity over UDP. Every transport path is quantum-safe; no classical-only channel exists in the production architecture.',
